#### Introduction
{:.pb-1}

When creating a _View_, you can opt to control the visibility of columns. These can be fully hidden while you are working with your data, hidden on both current and output _Views_, or initially hidden (but visible when required).

#### Adjusting Visibility
{:.pt-2 .pb-1}

![Hide Column Options Screenshot][1]{:class="img-fluid img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block"}

When you have __clicked__ on a __column heading__ you can use the __Visibility__ button menu (shown above) to control how a column is seen.

+ __Hide Now__ - Will be hidden from your __current__ working view (you can restore it using the __Show / Hide Columns__ command on the _Settings_ menu).
+ __Hide Always__ - This will both hide the column __immediately__, and hide it on the __output view__ too.
+ __Hide Initially__ - This will allow the column to be shown/hidden on both the output and your current view. The default state on the output view will be hidden, but restoring it is just a simple click away!

An __initially__ hidden column in its visible state (below):

![Column Visible Screenshot][2]{:class="img-fluid img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block"}

The __same__ column in it's __hidden__ state:

![Column Hidden Screenshot][3]{:class="img-fluid img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block"}

#### Changing All Columns
{:.pt-2 .pb-1}

If you want to control the visibility of a lot of columns in one go, or need to restore a previously hidden column, then you can use the __Show / Hide Columns__ command on the _Settings_ menu.

![Change All Columns Screenshot][4]{:class="img-fluid img-thumbnail mx-auto d-block"}

The dialog displayed (shown above) will indicate the current state of each column, and also provide a __quick__ route to the visibility of as many columns as you wish. Simply set the appropriate menus to your desired values and click the __Apply__ button.
